{"id":"2212.03656","submitter":"Yuki Yasuda Ph.D.","authors":"Yuki Yasuda and Ryo Onishi","title":"Spatio-Temporal Super-Resolution Data Assimilation (SRDA) Utilizing Deep\n  Neural Networks with Domain Generalization Technique Toward Four-Dimensional\n  SRDA","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Deep learning has recently gained attention in atmospheric and oceanic\nsciences for its potential to improve the accuracy of numerical simulations and\nreduce computational costs. Super-resolution is one such technique, which\nobtains high-resolution inference from low-resolution data. This paper proposes\na new data assimilation scheme, called four-dimensional super-resolution data\nassimilation (4D-SRDA). This framework calculates the time evolution of a\nsystem from low-resolution simulations by an atmospheric or ocean model,\nwhereas a trained neural network simultaneously performs data assimilation and\nspatio-temporal super-resolution. The use of low-resolution simulations without\nensemble members reduces the computational cost of obtaining high-resolution\npredictions in space and time. In 4D-SRDA, fluid simulations and neural-network\ninferences are conducted alternately, which can lead to domain shifts, i.e.,\nstatistical differences in forecast states between the training and testing\nphases. Such domain shifts may reduce the accuracy of inferences. To enhance\nthe robustness of inferences in 4D-SRDA, super-resolution mixup (SR-mixup) is\ndeveloped, which is a data augmentation method for domain generalization.\nSR-mixup creates a linear combination of randomly sampled inputs, which\nvirtually follows different distributions from the original data. The validity\nof 4D-SRDA and SR-mixup is demonstrated through numerical experiments of an\nidealized barotropic ocean jet with supervised learning. The results suggest\nthat the combination of 4D-SRDA and SR-mixup is useful for robust inference,\nparticularly when observation points are spatially sparse. This research\nindicates the potential of super-resolution and domain generalization\ntechniques, in terms of data assimilation, for the future integration of\nmachine learning and physics-based models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Dec 2022 14:21:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-08"}
